South Korea Stocks: Samsung Life, Daekyung, Value Added Tech

-- B y   J u n   Y a n g
-- 
2011-07-18T00:51:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-18/south-korea-stocks-samsung-life-daekyung-value-added-tech.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in South Korea trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 9:30 a.m. in Seoul. The  Kospi
Index (KOSPI)  slipped 13.25, or 0.6 percent, to 2,131.95.  Daekyung Machinery & Engineering Co. (015590 KS) surged 12
percent to 4,100 won. The Korea Economic Daily reported that
Daewoo Shipbuilding & Marine Co. is considering buying the
company. Daewoo was asked by the stock exchange to clarify the
report by 12:00 p.m. today.  Samsung Life Insurance Co. (032830 KS) rose 3.4 percent to
98,600 won. The company plans to buy back 3 million shares,
according to a filing. In a separate filing, the company said it
will spend 652.8 billion won ($615 million) to develop
commercial land in Beijing.  Value Added Technologies Co. (043150 KS), a medical-
equipment maker, jumped 12 percent to 10,850 won. Samsung
Electronics Co. is in talks to buy makers of MRI scanners and X-
Ray machines, Senior Vice President Jo Jae Moon, who leads a
team of medical-equipment developers, said in an interview on
July 15.  To contact the reporters on this story:
